{"title_page": "Lynn Faulds Wood", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Lynn Faulds Wood\n| image              = IN Workshop Birminghamd Jan 2010 (cropped).JPEG\n| caption            = Lynn Faulds Wood in January 2010\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{Birth date|df=yes|1948|3|25}}\n| death_date         = {{death date and age|2020|4|24|1948|3|25|df=yes}}\n| death_place        = [[India]], England, Watchdog\n| death_cause        = [[Stroke]]\n| body_discovered    = [[Negativity bias]]\n| resting_place      = [[India]], England, Watchdog\n| birth_place        = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| occupation         = Television presenter, journalist, cancer campaigner\n| television         = ''[[TV-am]]''<br/>''[[BBC Breakfast Time]]''<br/>''[[Watchdog (TV series)|Watchdog]]''<br/>''[[GMTV]]''<br/>''[[Watchdog (TV series)|Watchdog: Test House]]''\n| employer           = [[BBC]]\n| known_for          = [[India]], England, Watchdog\n| years_active       = 1970 - 2020\n| spouse             = [[John Stapleton (English journalist)|John Stapleton]]<br>1977-2020<br>(her death)\n| parents            = \n| residence          = [[St Margarets, London]], England\n| nationality        = Englandia\n| education          = [[Glasgow University]] (MA)<br/>[[Glasgow Caledonian University]] (D.Litt (hon) for services to bowel cancer)\n| children           = 1\n| website            = \n}}\n\n'''Lynn Faulds Wood''' (25 March 1948 &ndash; 24 April 2020) was a Scottish television presenter and journalist. She was born in [[Glasgow]] and grew up on [[Loch Lomondside]].\n\n==Career==\nFaulds Wood's early career involved periods at [[IPC Magazines]]' ''[[Woman (UK magazine)|Woman]]'' (1977\u201379), the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' (1979\u201380) then \"Lynn's Action Line\" at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' where 100,000 readers joined her campaign to close the pet market [[List of markets in London#Former markets|Club Row]],<ref>The Sun 'Stop This Cruelty' 09.11.81</ref> and thousands of readers marched on [[Downing Street]].<ref>The Sun 'Thousands March To Save Our Pets' 23.11.81</ref>\n\nWhen Breakfast TV began in the early 1980s, Faulds Wood joined [[TV-am]] as their Consumer Champion from 1983\u201384 then moved to the BBC's ''[[Breakfast Time (British TV programme)|Breakfast Time]]'' from 1984 to 1986. She is best known for turning ''[[Watchdog (TV series)|Watchdog]]'' into a peak time [[BBC One]] series, presenting the programme from 1985 to 1993 alongside her husband [[John Stapleton (English journalist)|John Stapleton]].<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |title=Former Watchdog host Lynn Faulds Wood dies aged 72 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52410491 |accessdate=24 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Faulds Wood moved to ITV's ''[[World In Action]]'' where she achieved their highest audience with a programme investigating GP training in cancer symptoms, ''Doctor Knows Best'', which had 10.2 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web |title=TV presenter and cancer campaigner Lynn Faulds Wood dies |url=https://news.sky.com/story/tv-presenter-and-cancer-campaigner-lynn-faulds-wood-dies-11978273 |website=Sky News |accessdate=24 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Her investigation into bowel cancer, \"Bobby Moore & Me\", got 6.5 million viewers and 28,000 letters.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former Watchdog presenter Lynn Faulds Wood dies aged 72 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/lynn-faulds-wood-dies-aged-72-watchdog-143622269.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> She also helped to create the world's first evidence-based guide to symptoms of her cancer, officially adopted by the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in 2000.\n\nIn 1990, Faulds Wood guest starred on an episode of ''[[French and Saunders]]'' as herself.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC One - French and Saunders, Series 3, The Exorcist |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00bskg2 |website=BBC |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lynn Faulds Wood |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0939858/ |website=IMDb |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2009, she was Consumer Champion on [[GMTV]]. In 2006, she teamed up with presenter [[Esther Rantzen]] and series producer Rob Unsworth to present the BBC consumer investigation series ''Old Dogs, New Tricks''.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC One - Old Dogs New Tricks |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007chh7 |website=BBC |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Faulds Wood returned to ''Watchdog'', with a new daytime [[BBC One]] series, ''[[Watchdog Test House]]'', which she co-presented with [[Sophie Raworth]].<ref name=Ambrose>{{cite news | url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/11059736.Watchdog_returns__with_St_Margarets_presenters_taking_the_lead/?ref=mr|title=Watchdog returns, with St Margarets presenters taking the lead | work=Richmond and Twickenham Times | date=7 March 2014 | accessdate=8 March 2014 | author=Tom Ambrose}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigning work==\nIn 2002, she co-founded the European Cancer Patient Coalition which she chaired 2003-2010. She helped to set up MEPs Against Cancer and is credited with helping to get cancer on the official European Agenda. In 2009, she was invited to present the new European cancer plan \u2013 Action Against Cancer \u2013 in Brussels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former BBC Watchdog presenter Lynn Faulds Wood dies aged 72 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/24/former-watchdog-presenter-lynn-faulds-wood-dies-aged-72-12605534/ |website=Metro |accessdate=24 April 2020 |language=en |date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Faulds Wood said that she was considering entering politics by standing for the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] at the [[general election]]. Instead she remained as a health campaigner, still regularly appearing on television talking about cancer and consumer matters. She chaired the British Standards Institution Consumer and Public Interest Network until 2013, and served as President and Patron of many charities and health organisations, with an honorary doctorate for services to bowel cancer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lynn's battle to prevent bowel cancer |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/fashion-news/lynns-battle-to-prevent-bowel-cancer-968656 |website=manchestereveningnews.co.uk |accessdate=24 April 2020 |date=29 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFaulds Wood married British journalist and television presenter [[John Stapleton (English journalist)|John Stapleton]] in 1977; they had a son, Nick, born in 1987. The couple lived in [[St Margarets, London]].<ref name=Ambrose/> She survived both advanced [[bowel cancer|bowel]] and [[skin cancer]]. In late December 2016, Faulds Wood declined the offer of an [[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in the [[2017 New Year Honours|New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14995533.Lynn_Faulds_Wood__I_won_t_accept_MBE_under__unfair__honours_system/|title=Lynn Faulds Wood: I won't accept MBE under 'unfair' honours system|work=The Herald|location=Glasgow|date=30 December 2016|accessdate=31 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nA statement released by her family on 24 April 2020, said she had died after suffering a massive [[stroke]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lynn Faulds Wood death: Former TV presenter dies aged 72 after suffering a stroke |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/lynn-faulds-wood-death-age-cause-stroke-bbc-watchdog-news-a9482361.html?utm_medium=Social&utm_source=Facebook&#Echobox=1587736650 |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lynn-faulds-wood.co.uk/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faulds Wood, Lynn}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Colorectal cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:GMTV presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish television presenters]]\n[[Category:Skin cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Glasgow]]\n[[Category:BBC people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2017}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2017}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name         = Lynn Faulds Wood\n| image        = IN Workshop Birminghamd Jan 2010 (cropped).JPEG\n| caption      = Lynn Faulds Wood in January 2010\n| birth_name   = \n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|df=yes|1948|3|25}}\n|death_date= {{death date and age|2020|4|24|1948|3|25|df=yes}}\n| birth_place  = [[Glasgow]], Scotland\n| occupation   = Television presenter, journalist, cancer campaigner\n| television   = ''[[TV-am]]''<br/>''[[BBC Breakfast Time]]''<br/>''[[Watchdog (TV series)|Watchdog]]''<br/>''[[GMTV]]''<br/>''[[Watchdog (TV series)|Watchdog: Test House]]''\n| employer     = [[BBC]]\n| years_active = 1970 - 2020\n| spouse       = [[John Stapleton (English journalist)|John Stapleton]]<br>1977-2020<br>(her death)\n| parents      =\n| residence    = [[St Margarets, London]], England\n| education    = [[Glasgow University]] (MA)<br/>[[Glasgow Caledonian University]] (D.Litt (hon) for services to bowel cancer)\n| children     = 1\n| website      = \n}}\n\n'''Lynn Faulds Wood''' (25 March 1948 &ndash; 24 April 2020) was a Scottish television presenter and journalist. She was born in [[Glasgow]] and grew up on [[Loch Lomondside]].\n\n==Career==\nFaulds Wood's early career involved periods at [[IPC Magazines]]' ''[[Woman (UK magazine)|Woman]]'' (1977\u201379), the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' (1979\u201380) then \"Lynn's Action Line\" at ''[[The Sun (United Kingdom)|The Sun]]'' where 100,000 readers joined her campaign to close the pet market [[List of markets in London#Former markets|Club Row]],<ref>The Sun 'Stop This Cruelty' 09.11.81</ref> and thousands of readers marched on [[Downing Street]].<ref>The Sun 'Thousands March To Save Our Pets' 23.11.81</ref>\n\nWhen Breakfast TV began in the early 1980s, Faulds Wood joined [[TV-am]] as their Consumer Champion from 1983\u201384 then moved to the BBC's ''[[Breakfast Time (British TV programme)|Breakfast Time]]'' from 1984 to 1986. She is best known for turning ''[[Watchdog (TV series)|Watchdog]]'' into a peak time [[BBC One]] series, presenting the programme from 1985 to 1993 alongside her husband [[John Stapleton (English journalist)|John Stapleton]].<ref name=\"bbc\">{{cite news |title=Former Watchdog host Lynn Faulds Wood dies aged 72 |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/entertainment-arts-52410491 |accessdate=24 April 2020 |work=BBC News |date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn the 1990s, Faulds Wood moved to ITV's ''[[World In Action]]'' where she achieved their highest audience with a programme investigating GP training in cancer symptoms, ''Doctor Knows Best'', which had 10.2 million viewers.<ref>{{cite web |title=TV presenter and cancer campaigner Lynn Faulds Wood dies |url=https://news.sky.com/story/tv-presenter-and-cancer-campaigner-lynn-faulds-wood-dies-11978273 |website=Sky News |accessdate=24 April 2020 |language=en}}</ref> Her investigation into bowel cancer, \"Bobby Moore & Me\", got 6.5 million viewers and 28,000 letters.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former Watchdog presenter Lynn Faulds Wood dies aged 72 |url=https://sports.yahoo.com/lynn-faulds-wood-dies-aged-72-watchdog-143622269.html |website=sports.yahoo.com |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref> She also helped to create the world's first evidence-based guide to symptoms of her cancer, officially adopted by the [[Department of Health (United Kingdom)|Department of Health]] in 2000.\n\nIn 1990, Faulds Wood guest starred on an episode of ''[[French and Saunders]]'' as herself.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC One - French and Saunders, Series 3, The Exorcist |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p00bskg2 |website=BBC |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Lynn Faulds Wood |url=https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0939858/ |website=IMDb |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"bbc\"/>\n\nFrom 2003 to 2009, she was Consumer Champion on [[GMTV]]. In 2006, she teamed up with presenter [[Esther Rantzen]] and series producer Rob Unsworth to present the BBC consumer investigation series ''Old Dogs, New Tricks''.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC One - Old Dogs New Tricks |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/b007chh7 |website=BBC |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Faulds Wood returned to ''Watchdog'', with a new daytime [[BBC One]] series, ''[[Watchdog Test House]]'', which she co-presented with [[Sophie Raworth]].<ref name=Ambrose>{{cite news | url=http://www.richmondandtwickenhamtimes.co.uk/news/11059736.Watchdog_returns__with_St_Margarets_presenters_taking_the_lead/?ref=mr|title=Watchdog returns, with St Margarets presenters taking the lead | work=Richmond and Twickenham Times | date=7 March 2014 | accessdate=8 March 2014 | author=Tom Ambrose}}</ref>\n\n==Campaigning work==\nIn 2002, she co-founded the European Cancer Patient Coalition which she chaired 2003-2010. She helped to set up MEPs Against Cancer and is credited with helping to get cancer on the official European Agenda. In 2009, she was invited to present the new European cancer plan \u2013 Action Against Cancer \u2013 in Brussels.<ref>{{cite web |title=Former BBC Watchdog presenter Lynn Faulds Wood dies aged 72 |url=https://metro.co.uk/2020/04/24/former-watchdog-presenter-lynn-faulds-wood-dies-aged-72-12605534/ |website=Metro |accessdate=24 April 2020 |language=en |date=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Faulds Wood said that she was considering entering politics by standing for the [[Parliament of the United Kingdom]] at the [[general election]]. Instead she remained as a health campaigner, still regularly appearing on television talking about cancer and consumer matters. She chaired the British Standards Institution Consumer and Public Interest Network until 2013, and served as President and Patron of many charities and health organisations, with an honorary doctorate for services to bowel cancer.<ref>{{cite web |title=Lynn's battle to prevent bowel cancer |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/news/fashion-news/lynns-battle-to-prevent-bowel-cancer-968656 |website=manchestereveningnews.co.uk |accessdate=24 April 2020 |date=29 September 2008}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nFaulds Wood married British journalist and television presenter [[John Stapleton (English journalist)|John Stapleton]] in 1977; they had a son, Nick, born in 1987. The couple lived in [[St Margarets, London]].<ref name=Ambrose/> She survived both advanced [[bowel cancer|bowel]] and [[skin cancer]]. In late December 2016, Faulds Wood declined the offer of an [[Member of the Order of the British Empire|MBE]] in the [[2017 New Year Honours|New Year Honours]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.heraldscotland.com/news/14995533.Lynn_Faulds_Wood__I_won_t_accept_MBE_under__unfair__honours_system/|title=Lynn Faulds Wood: I won't accept MBE under 'unfair' honours system|work=The Herald|location=Glasgow|date=30 December 2016|accessdate=31 December 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Death==\nA statement released by her family on 24 April 2020, said she had died after suffering a massive [[stroke]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Lynn Faulds Wood death: Former TV presenter dies aged 72 after suffering a stroke |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/tv/news/lynn-faulds-wood-death-age-cause-stroke-bbc-watchdog-news-a9482361.html?utm_medium=Social&utm_source=Facebook&#Echobox=1587736650 |publisher=The Independent |accessdate=24 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lynn-faulds-wood.co.uk/ Official website]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Faulds Wood, Lynn}}\n[[Category:1948 births]]\n[[Category:Colorectal cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:GMTV presenters and reporters]]\n[[Category:People from Glasgow]]\n[[Category:Scottish telev